The big return of the Czech loser is approaching.
Pavel Francouz called up to the NHL
Czech ice hockey goaltender Pavel Francouz, who is going through a difficult period in his career, returns to the NHL.
The 31-year-old native of Pilsen will be on the bench, and soon could find himself in the goal.
The former goalkeeper of Litvínov, Plzeň or Russian Chelyabinsk was injured during preparation for the NHL in October this year.
He was replaced at the half-way point of the game with Vegas and has not been seen on NHL ice since.
The incident happened as the experienced goalkeeper moved from one post to another.
"Pavel Francouz will be out approximately three to four weeks with a lower-body injury," the Avalanche announced at the beginning of October.
His return to the net in the NHL ended up lasting more than two months.
He was called up from the farm Sunday morning U.S. time, where he caught four games and showed his old form.
In the AHL, he recorded a save percentage of 94.5%.
The graduate of the Plzeň hockey school wants to finally make it and prove that he belongs in the best league in the world.
He had trouble with his hip in the last season and in the shortened pandemic season, he didn't play a single game.
In the NHL, "Francík" has played 36 games, and his success rate is 92.3%.
