According to efotbal.cz, Slavia promised Berbr a million for the title, Tvrdík denied it.
Prague - Investigators in the current corruption case are allegedly working on the assumption that the accused former deputy chairman of the Czech Football Association, Roman Berbr, was promised a million Czech crowns from Slavia Prague for the league title in the 2018/19 season.
The website efotbal.cz reported this, stating that it had obtained part of the police files.
The chairman of the board of directors of the Vršovice club, Jaroslav Tvrdík, stated that the white-and-reds did not engage in any corrupt activities.
The website published a transcript of police recordings, in which Slavia is mainly represented by its former sporting director Jan Nezmar, who left the championship club last summer.
According to the report, the former influential official of the red-and-whites was in frequent contact with Berbr as well as the former sporting director of the then second-division Vyšehrad, Roman Rogoz, who is also among the accused in the case.
The investigators were allegedly working with information that Slavia had promised Berbatov a financial reward for winning the title.
In 2019, the SK Slavia Prague team won the first league title.
The police authority had knowledge that Roman (Berbr) was promised a million-dollar bribe by SK Slavia Prague functionaries for winning the league, the server quoted from the file.
The day after, according to the criminal investigators, Berbr met not only with Nezmar, but also with the chairman of the Slavia board, Tvrdík.
According to the server, it is not clear whether the police are still dealing with this information.
Tvrdík denied any corruption.
Between 2015 and 2017, we actively tried to change the state of affairs in Czech football and offered an alternative to its development.
We have never committed any illegal act, we have never tried to influence referees in violation of the fair play rules, and we have not provided anyone with any financial compensation in this regard," said Tvrdík for Seznam Zprávy.
In the recordings, Nezmar insults some of Slavia's former dark-skinned players and also defames his former boss, Tvrdík.
The case of alleged match-fixing through referees was triggered by a police raid in mid-October last year at several locations, including the FAČR headquarters in Prague.
Berbr is the highest-ranking person involved in the scandal, and he is no longer involved in any football functions.
In mid-January, he was released from custody, just like the former sports director of Vyšehrad, Rogoz.
Helicopters, tanks and BVPs are LARPing the Cold War.
The new tanks will be of a fundamentally worse type (the gunners will have to fire from a armoured cabin and carry the cartridges by hand without protection).
The cars - Toyota Hi-luxes - are new and good
Trucks and various armoured vehicles - at a decent level, in addition, it has been possible to get rid of the Praga V3S in specialist units.
Aircraft: combat - decent, but at the end of the lease, passenger - too small with a short range, but modern.
Drones - few and only small types with no combat potential
Rockets - we don't have any (but we produce them and export them abroad)
NGOs: Cold War, outdated; short-range: good, modern, relatively good numbers.
I have a story like that.
I have my hunting grounds right next to the city.
The nutria were climbing out of the river and doing damage to the crops, so I was there to sit on them.
When I arrived, I saw a fisherman on the other side of the river.
I didn't want to make a scene, so I quietly sat down and the guy probably didn't notice me.
I was hoping he would leave before anything came out, but of course the fox came out after a while.
I let her come to 40 meters before I decided to shoot.
The poor fisherman almost pooped his pants, he was waving his headtorch all over the place, so I called out to him that it was a fox.
When I got down from the saddle, I was exhausted.
In other words, a man's meadow can be a prude.
On the other hand, it's not a war, it would take a lot of coincidences for something to happen, you'd probably be seen on thermal imaging, which almost everyone has today.
So put it in a visible place, put your expensive things in your sleeping bag, and you should be fine.
