I respect the soldiers and the army (I am probably not affected by the memories of the ČSLA, which the older generations went through), but the Czech Republic cannot benefit from compulsory military service.
We don't even have large stockpiles of equipment that the trained reservists could use, we don't even have modern equipment for the current professionals, and on top of that, modern equipment is getting more and more complicated, so the abilities of the reservists will rapidly decline over time.
To this, modern conventional conflicts, where anyone can be deployed, will take place very quickly, and there won't be time to train someone again.
Finally, the reservists/territorial defence are of great importance for countries like Ukraine, where it is necessary to conduct mass guerrilla warfare, and it is also a necessity to deter the enemy.
In the Czech Republic, we will only be able to fight in a conflict of such size and intensity that guerrilla warfare will be irrelevant, and we do not have the appropriate geography for that.
Above all, we don't have individual skill.
And that's not even the worst of it.
The worst thing is that half of them are playing like they have it.
Then such situations occur, where you look like a guy who missed an open net 2 minutes ago, drives into the attack alone between 2 or even 3 Swiss players and ask yourself "what do you think is going to happen now?".
Of course, they will take him as an average taxpayer.
The situation with this skill of "beating a defender" is so bad that I have been honestly surprised when I see that our attacker managed to beat one of the opponent's players.
Early signs
The Covid-19 pandemic is slowing down, however, experts do not expect any major change in the coming weeks.
The pressure on hospitals will continue for some time, according to statistical models, and a new unknown has been added to the pandemic equation: the Omicron variant, which is very likely to spread faster than the currently dominant Delta.
At the same time, it is not yet possible to say with absolute certainty whether it can cause a more serious course of the disease, to what extent vaccination or post-infection immunity acquired from a previous infection can help.
This week, however, an unexpected phenomenon on the plus side entered the COVID equation: the possibility of treatment.
The new drug, the antiviral molnupiravir, has arrived in the Czech Republic. This drug reduces the risk of a severe course of the disease and the associated hospitalisation by a third, and it is possible to take it at home.
Soon it should also be joined by Pfizer's paxlovid drug, which, according to preliminary results, has a success rate of up to 85 per cent.
The first deliveries of molnupiravir to the Czech Republic, in addition to the hope of expanding the portfolio of tools useful in the fight against the coronavirus pandemic, have also highlighted the question of how the Czech administration is prepared for the arrival of new drugs.
As mentioned, the first one to reach Czech patients will be Merck's molnupiravir.
The company ended up at the front of the line because the drug had been in development for a long time before the current pandemic, with the aim of finding a suitable treatment for a viral disease of horses in South America.
These studies often overlook the fact that people in the West (Germany, Sweden, etc.)
are generally less open and don't share their opinions as freely.
In contrast, Eastern Europeans, and especially us Czechs, are used to speaking "as if a beak grew on our nose".
So you do research where you ask people if they like Muslims.
Most people in the Czech Republic will tell you straight out that they don't.
In the West, they will tell you how much they love immigration, how everyone should help them and how we Czechs are a racist bunch.
And then they go and vote for parties like the AfD.
They fear cancel culture, saying this in public means losing your job and media lynching.
Then in the polls it looks nice, the West is good, the East is bad.
But they'll find out what people really think.
