In the second grade of elementary school, we had a Gypsy classmate, and we were together for 4 years.
He was pretty good, made some good jokes, he was a bit over the top sometimes, but he was like our mascot.
Everybody was talking to him, he often came back and wanted to explain something, he was almost always there, he did sports with us, he didn't steal snacks or phones, he came neatly dressed.
He also went to outdoor schools, did all sorts of monkey business, but he was fine, he never had any mishaps.
In the 8th or 9th grade, the siblings, the Roma, entered the same class, other classes.
Soon after, they beat up a teacher, the police were often there, they threatened and bullied other students...
I occasionally sell things on the classifieds (old stuff, things I don't need, etc.) and I've often sold them to Gypsies, they always had the money, they didn't try to haggle with me, the communication was calm.
I even sold a car like this, the guy called a month later, saying that he had already transferred it to his name...
I say myself that I'm not a racist, I don't care if someone is white, black, yellow, blue or anything else, as long as they act as they should in a decent society (work, function, don't beat women, just normal behaviour).
But when someone comes, they stretch out their hand, they move into flats and houses, they leave a mess around them, they cause problems... it doesn't matter what colour they are, but I won't like them.
I have no problem with African migrants if they get involved, start a business, work, learn the language (not necessarily, at least English), and respect our culture.
If they believe in Allah, I don't care, as long as they respect my traditions and culture, I will respect theirs.
A young woman died in a car crash in Prachatice
"The young woman suffered serious multiple injuries and, despite resuscitation efforts, unfortunately succumbed to her injuries at the scene," said Zuzana Fajtlová, the spokesperson for the South Bohemian Emergency Medical Service, to Právo.
The accident was probably caused by the driver who was taking the girl.
The 18-year-old driver of the Peugeot was probably travelling from the village of Žíchovec towards the village of Bavorov, and for yet unknown reasons veered into oncoming traffic in a bend.
After a collision with a Skoda Octavia, the Peugeot ended up on its roof off the road, said South Bohemian police spokeswoman Štěpánka Schwarzová.
The young driver of the Peugeot sustained very serious injuries in the crash.
He sustained multiple injuries and was trapped in the car.
After being freed, he had to be given emergency pre-hospital care and was then airlifted to the hospital in České Budějovice in a stable condition, said rescuer Fajtlová.
She added that the man in the second car suffered minor chest injuries and was taken to hospital.
New rules for parcels from non-EU countries, customers often fail to provide details
Lukáš Neuheisl orders from abroad several times a month.
It mainly collects collector's cards.
"Usually it's tens of dollars, say from ten dollars upwards, where it still pays to import, especially from Japan, where the post is often free," explains the collector.
Since October, ordering small parcels has become slightly more expensive, and they must now add VAT, and pass on details to the post office for customs procedures.
He will receive an e-mail stating that the customs officers are awaiting the arrival of the package.
Then all you have to do is fill in the information about the package, and if the seller did not include VAT in the sale, the customs office will calculate it from the total amount for the package and delivery.
If the recipient does not take care of the customs clearance themselves, they must also add the transport fee to the total amount.
According to Lukáš Neuheisl, however, the whole process is not complicated.
I tick one or two check boxes, attach two attachments, and I'm done.
For me, it is usually a matter of five minutes, says Neuheisl.
Not all deliveries go off without a hitch, though.
Due to new customs regulations, the daily number of packages received at the international post office in Prague fell from 60,000 to 15,000.
According to Czech Post, the problem is also that people do not respond to requests for information needed to complete customs procedures.
There are currently 30,000 parcels on the international post, which we have to process.
If people were to fill in all the information that is needed and fill it in on time, we would be about halfway there, says Matyáš Vitík, a spokesman for the Czech Post.
Solving the Inflation Problem
See the title, how would you suggest a solution to the current inflation?
Currently we are at 9.9% inflation and it is expected to rise further.
What do you think it should do to slow down or compensate for this growth?
We can see, for example, the reduction of VAT on foodstuffs and PHM in Poland. Is this the way for you?
What do you think will happen, which is inevitable with where it's headed?
Prices are rising faster than wages, and it's inevitable that people won't be able to afford the things they need, especially energy.
How much did you get added, for example (who is an employee)?
They added 2% to my gross this year, which is a joke, but luckily I have a similar income from a business that I run alongside my job.
