How to avoid drowning in the box-tipping tsunami
You unwrap the presents under the Christmas tree and all of a sudden you're surrounded by boxes and packing materials at home?
This "waste" is being re-used by online shops that are short of packaging materials.
A map has been created of shops that will welcome your used boxes.
And not just at Christmas.
All packaging materials are designed to withstand repeated handling.
That's why it's a shame to treat them as single-use waste.
Anyone can bring cardboard boxes, plastic or paper fillers to the participating stores (the KAMsNIM.cz project map contains nearly 150 of them).
This will support small businesses, reduce the amount of waste produced and also avoid overcrowded blue bins.
The shops themselves welcome the packaging, which is currently in short supply on the market, and also the saved money, as the cardboard packaging has increased in price by 50% over the last period.
In the eyes of ecologically-minded customers, I am strengthening my brand.
One of these shops is TIERRA VERDE, a manufacturer of eco-cosmetics and eco-cosmetics.
The boxes and packing materials are brought to us in Popůvky near Brno by individuals who have accumulated them at home, but we also hear from companies with whom we have agreed regular collections of discarded cardboard.
We will use it to package shipments from our e-shop.
Thanks to individuals and companies, we are creating a more considerate world.
Our wish is to preserve the resources and beauty of nature for future generations, says Petra Lopušníková from Tierry.
However, the www.KAMsNIM.cz application shows not only collection points for packaging.
It serves as a search engine if you need to get rid of anything (where to take sorted household waste, where to deliver expired medicines, tyres, retired electrical appliances, batteries, light sources, large-volume waste, etc.).
All waste can thus end up in the right place, and reusable items can find their second home.
The project's map already includes more than 100,000 such places.
"More and more collection points, re-use centres, textile containers, food banks, charity shops, SWAPs and other places that help find a use for things that would otherwise become waste are being added to it," adds Miroslav Kubásek, one of the authors of the app from the Ukliďme Česko association.
I think it's more concerning that technology is so simple and idiot-proof that children who use a computer or phone to play games don't learn basic computer skills.
Recently there has been a problem (especially in English articles) that university students do not understand the principle of computer components.
Because things like Google Photos or Apple's photo app or really mobile phones in general just hide the underlying filesystem with folders and just put everything on one screen in the app.
They can use the technique from childhood, but above all, they should learn something.
Let's rewrite history, seriously
Emmanuel Macron unveiled the priorities of France's EU presidency - beginning in January - over the weekend, and it was grand.
Macron spoke for over an hour, during which he unveiled the logo for the presidency, called for the protection of Europeans - at work and on the street - and mentioned so many actions that they cannot be completed in half a year.
French politicians like it that way and so do the voters.
Macron's supporters, divided between the right and the left, agree on little, but they do agree on Europe.
And in France, there will be new elections for the head of state in April.
The election calendar also influenced the priorities.
The French leader, among other things, mentioned that historians should write "one history of Europe" and France is ready to create conditions for such work by historians.
A number of commentators were quick to criticise Macron's pro-European propaganda and rewriting of history.
In fact, they are trying to prevent the rewriting of history.
Far-right French presidential candidate Eric Zemmour is currently touring France with the claim that the Vichy regime, which collaborated with Hitler during the Second World War, was not so bad, and he is having some success with it.
Let's take Macron's idea of a single history textbook seriously and not look at what is happening in France.
Is it needed?
Students in European countries are often taught history as a story of us versus them, and never as a story of the whole.
Spaniards, French, and Czechs are learning who beat whom in which battle.
But without a wise cantor, they won't know the wider context of the event.
