We are adding the books to this digital edition for you, our subscribers, so that you have enough time to buy the books as Christmas presents.
The prose texts follow on from the previous similar collection Petříček Sellier & Petříček Bellot.
Another helping of observation of the world and description of everyday things with uncommonly poetic attention to detail, depth, and atmosphere.
In his second novel, the photographer Šesták tried to capture the essence of a small town and Czech society.
The story of returning to one's roots, which turns out to be just a longed-for illusion.
The bohemist and comparatist transfers the fairy tale of Red Riding Hood to the setting of a contemporary village.
Its delivery is more brutal than the folk versions and escalates into a horror of emotional emptiness.
And that the path back to instincts is shorter than we are willing to admit
The author tells a less sentimental story about returning from emigration in his penultimate novel than we are used to listening to.
Those who stayed and those who left know too little about each other to make it work.
The trains will start running according to the new timetable, in some places the operators will change
From Sunday, trains will be running according to a new timetable.
The biggest change is the replacement of transport providers on some routes, for example between Ústí nad Labem and Kolín, where RegioJet is replacing České dráhy.
For most lines, only the departure time will be changed, and in some cases, the route will be changed slightly.
There will also be dozens of new trains on the tracks.
The transport companies started selling tickets as early as in the autumn.
České dráhy are planning to run an average of 6,783 passenger services per day in the new timetable, including an average of 478 long-distance trains per day.
The trains will cover approximately 118 million kilometres during the new timetable.
In addition to the domestic connections, the new timetable will also include routes to Germany, Poland, Slovakia, Hungary, Austria and Switzerland.
The company will introduce dozens of new trains along with the new timetable.
The main novelty will be the InterJet trains, which will run on the Prague-Cheb line.
The transport company is sending other new trains to the north of Moravia or in western Bohemia.
The transport company will also traditionally raise ticket prices next year, by an average of 3.2 per cent.
The railways take inflation into account in their tariffs every year.
The biggest change in the RegioJet timetable is the entry into the R23 line Ústí nad Labem - Mělník - Nymburk - Kolín.
The transport company will replace České dráhy here after its success in the Ministry of Transport's competition.
RegioJet will operate a total of 16 trains on the route every day, eight in each direction.
Other changes affect long-distance trains between Prague and Brno, which will stop at Havlíčkův Brod, Žďár nad Sázavou and Kolín from Sunday.
Leo Express retained its 16 connections, two return connections to Slovakia and the weekend connection to Krakow.
According to spokesman Emil Sedlář, the transport company tried to keep the schedules of its long-distance trains as similar as possible despite the planned maintenance work.
Without major changes, the operation of Arriva trains and other carriers should also continue.
Transport providers will also be exchanged on some regional routes.
There will be changes for passengers, for example in the Českolipsko area, where instead of Czech Railways, the Trilex trains of the German company Die Länderbahn will run on the line from Mladá Boleslav via Česká Lípa to Rumburk.
Travellers will also be able to use a single ticket on the railway for the second year in a row.
Just like České dráhy, their prices will increase by 3.2 per cent due to inflation.
I have to disagree.
Aren't we supposed to learn the other side of the story?
Everywhere we hear how much they had to fight for their rights, how they were oppressed and had to work hard and die.
In my life, I've never heard a sermon from the perspective of the slave-owning side or from that time, nobody is defending it, they're just condemning it.
No one tells you in school that black people often sold other black people into slavery and that they were often the worst slave owners.
No one will teach you at school that the colonisers often bought the land from the Indians; they will only tell you how brutally we, the Europeans, exterminated them, although they were killing each other long before us.
I also spent some time in the USA, directly at the schools, both in the north and in the south.
I have not encountered anyone deliberately covering up facts, but I have heard before that it happens, and I think it's a problem (for example, in Japan, the atrocities of WW2 are quite a taboo).
My point is that history is not black and white and that we have a tendency to look at it from today's perspective, without understanding.
History is not interested in people's feelings, it is just what it is, and I think it is a fatal mistake to condemn without looking at things from that time.
On the other hand, we should learn from it and never do this again.
By the way, while we're on the subject of southern states, yes, the Confederate flag and famous slave owners are quite popular there, on the other hand they also had some of their own successes, and it seemed absurd to me to reject them.
Moreover, the North was not much better, as many people idealise it today.
And a lot of people also forget that not everyone in the South were slave owners and a lot of things bothered them too.
I wouldn't compare this to the Russians, they deliberately leave out some facts, lie and manipulate, and our point of view doesn't exist (there was a video on YouTube from a TV channel, where they cut off someone who started talking about our legionnaires and 1968).
What I found funny about US schools was the rise of Marxism and the idealization of communism, something their country has never experienced.
Overall, I found that at some universities it was terrible, those students were quite radicalised and the universities often supported them.
And when I think that these people will be much older in the future, I am a little bit worried that this could be the voice of the majority, because it is among the young and even in the ruling elite.
I think that, for example, feminism has already achieved what it set out to and it's no longer about the same thing, it has become radicalised.
