TV has fallen out of love with Christmas films, with just 200 premiering this year
Los Angeles - Movie theaters, TV channels and streaming platforms in the United States and other English-speaking countries have fallen into the trend of Christmas movies and this year will premiere a record number of more than two hundred of them.
The operator of the IMDb film database did the count.
In recent years, the genre of Christmas family and romantic films has scored with the audience and significantly increased its popularity, so more and more of these films are being produced.
This year, four times as many Christmas films were made as in 2011 and twice as many as five years ago.
The IMDb database, however, includes only those films that have the word Christmas in their title, so there are actually many more Christmas films.
The movies that people traditionally associate with Christmas have always existed.
In the Czech Republic, this period is associated with fairy tales; worldwide, films such as Home Alone, Love Actually or the classic Christmas story It's a Wonderful Life from 1946 are popular.
The real boom in Christmas movies started in 2009, when the American cable television channel Hallmark came up with a special movie series, recalled the BBC website.
Her Christmas project, called Countdown to Christmas, at the time included four films and was very successful.
This year, this station started to tune its viewers in for Christmas as early as 22 October, and will show a total of 42 Christmas films.
Competitor network Lifetime has 35 new holiday-themed films on its schedule this year, and popular streaming services like Netflix are also contributing to the total.
"In this magical time of year, the story doesn't matter so much, it's just important that there's a lot of Christmas trees in the background and it's snowing," said Brandon Gray, author of the book I'll Be Home for Christmas Movies.
"It's a form of escapism for the audience and a way to feel a little bit of calm for at least two hours in the midst of all of this Christmas madness and the madness of the world we've been living in for the last few years," Gray added.
According to him, for example, Hallmark TV uses the same recipe for its films, which is uniform, but successful.
You have two people who fall in love with each other, but then there is a misunderstanding about half an hour before the end, which is successfully resolved and the two of them kiss.
That's the way it's always been, and as long as all the films look the same and have the same atmosphere, people are going to watch them one after the other, Gray added.
