California will restrict gun sales.
It wants to follow Texas's lead on banning abortions.
California Gov. Gavin Newsom on Saturday announced a plan to ban the sale and manufacture of some guns in the nation's most populous state by using the same legal mechanism that Texas used in its controversial abortion law that bans abortions after a fetal heartbeat is detected.
People would then have the right to sue anyone who manufactures or sells assault weapons and homemade guns in California.
Newsom's announcement came in response to a Friday ruling by the U.S. Supreme Court, which left in place a Texas ban on abortions, even though it goes against a nearly 50-year-old precedent that established a right to abortion nationwide up until about 24 weeks of pregnancy.
However, the court was not now ruling on the constitutionality of the entire law, but on a technical issue arising from the innovative construction of the measure.
In this case, enforcement of the ban was delegated to the public, making it impossible for Texas Republicans to challenge it in court.
"I'm outraged by yesterday's (Friday) decision by the United States Supreme Court to uphold the Texas ban on most abortions and to largely endorse Texas's scheme to protect its law," the California governor said.
"If states can now block review of their laws by federal courts, then California will exercise that authority to save lives," Newsom continued.
He reportedly tasked his subordinates to work with the state parliament and the justice minister on measures that would allow representatives of the public to enforce the ban on assault rifles and so-called ghost guns.
These are home-made guns that do not have serial numbers and can be used to circumvent regulations.
Newsom wants to give "private citizens" the right to sue for at least $10,000 (220,000 CZK) and legal fees from anyone who manufactures, distributes or sells assault rifles, "ghost gun" parts or kits to make them in California.
"If the most effective way to keep these deadly weapons off our streets is to create the threat of private litigation, then that's exactly what we should do," the California governor said.
The Associated Press notes that California has banned the manufacture and sale of some military-style weapons for decades, but a federal judge blocked the state's ban in June as unconstitutional.
If the state were to now actually reinstate the ban using the Texas model, it would confirm the words of liberal Supreme Court Justice Sonia Sotomayor, who in a dissenting opinion to Friday's majority ruling warned against expanding the legal mechanism to other states.
However, the Supreme Court did not grant the Texas ban full immunity from judicial review, allowing abortion clinics to continue to sue certain officials in the southern U.S. state.
