I was punished with a rolling pin as a child.
It was never about the marks, it was usually just that I repeatedly refused to listen and misbehaved (read instead of going to bed, argued with my brother, etc).
At the same time, I have never been punished without a warning. My mother always first threatened that if I did it again, I would get a slap (sometimes even after another "scolding" with a spoon, she would only bring it and place it so that I could see it).
Only after repeatedly refusing to listen did I get a couple of slaps on the back (through my clothing).
Personally, I think that physical punishment (in a reasonable manner and degree) is beneficial, because the child reacts to it much more than to words.
I think the important part is the warning, because it gives the child a choice whether to disobey and get a punishment, or to improve and not get a punishment.
I usually only needed a warning before I started to listen.
Defence of the system
When prominent Czech lawyer and constitutional court judge Vojtěch Cepl answered a journalist's question in 1999 as to what the Czech constitution meant to him - whether it was a sacred document to which one swears an oath and about which one is taught in school from a young age, or, on the contrary, an agreement that can be changed if necessary - he definitely inclined towards the first interpretation.
We once agreed on the democratic rules of our life, which at the same time define who we are as a state and its citizens, and changes are better saved.
And imagine this: some nations even like their rules.
Just as Czechs like dumplings with pork and cabbage, said Vojtěch Cepl at the time.
However, in recent times, there has been an increasing number of opinions among lawyers that the Czech Constitution needs to be changed.
Over the years, it has been tested by situations that its creators (including Vojtěch Cepl) could not foresee, such as the behaviour of the directly elected president.
But there was one thing that Cepl was right about.
Everything we know about such documents suggests that political interference in their wording must be deliberate.
Institutions must be understood and actively protected, only then can they be the key to dealing with most of the crises that societies have faced throughout history.
A constitution is, among other things, a set of rules of governance that sets the limits of the game for politicians.
We fear that power will be abused against minorities or individuals, so we tie the hands of politicians with restrictions.
At the same time, the constitutional texts also allow politicians to abuse their power.
Covid doesn't discriminate: several-month-old baby fighting for life at Brno University Hospital
Although it is known that the coronavirus is generally milder in children, there are also severe cases, which hospitals are mainly dealing with in recent times.
"We know that children are at less risk than adults, there is talk of 2 to 5 per cent compared to adults," said the head of the Pediatric Anesthesiology and Resuscitation Clinic at the University Hospital in Brno and the Faculty of Medicine at Masaryk University, Petr Dominik, to Novinky.cz.
The course is usually much less severe, lighter, and often symptom-free.
However, there are child patients who are severely ill with the coronavirus, which we are seeing particularly in recent times," added Dominik.
According to the doctor, it is about dozens of children who need mild supportive care.
It takes place at the Children's Infectious Diseases Clinic.
Children who are very seriously ill with the coronavirus have only recently been admitted to the ICU.
According to the doctor, children with post-COVID syndromes were admitted to the ward continuously throughout the year.
"Now there's an increase in kids with acute COVID pneumonia, that means inflammation of the lung that requires admission to the intensive care unit," he said, adding that the illness affects not only adults but also adolescents and babies as young as a few months old.
There are also children in critical condition due to COVID-19 in hospitals.
"We currently have a child of several months of age and an adolescent here," said the head of the department.
She is happy, however, that the children's hospital at the Brno University Hospital has not yet recorded any child deaths due to the coronavirus.
According to available data, six children aged 0-14 died in the Czech Republic on December 6.
According to Dominik, a psychologist is an essential part of the team in a children's hospital - not just in the COVID-19 ward.
At the same time, it also points out that just like in adults, vaccination also reduces the severity of the disease and at the same time reduces the occurrence of post-COVID syndrome in children.
"That's why we recommend the application of the vaccine dose in children as well," added the doctor.
