He then finished him off with a series of precise blows to record his 15th triumph.
Kara-France then beat Cody Garbrandt.
Nunes celebrated another triumph with her little daughter in the spring, now, seven years later, she has lost.
That hip or that hip?
At first glance, it doesn't seem like anything complicated.
Most nouns in Czech express only one grammatical gender, so there is no problem in determining whether it is masculine, feminine or neuter.
There is also a fairly large group of nouns whose gender is not fixed.
Such substantives oscillate between two genders.
When declined, they take on double endings and in some cases remain in the uninflected form.
For example, the words "svizel" and "kyčel" are of both masculine and feminine gender, in the first case they are inflected according to the "machine" paradigm, in the second case according to the "song" paradigm.
Another group of nouns have different forms in the first singular case, for example: "řádek/řádka", "kedluben/kedlubna" or "brambor/brambora" (in the sense of food).
Both forms are grammatically correct, have the same meaning, and are therefore freely interchangeable.
Some words vary regionally, for example "okurka" in Bohemia and "okurek" in Moravia, but in this case, the Moravian variant is non-standard, as are other Czech-Moravian pairs of words: "příkop" and "příkopa", "kobliha" and "koblih", etc.
Some words that entered Czech from other languages were originally uninflected, but are gradually taking on Czech endings.
A typical example is the word "image", which is both masculine and feminine, or the word "buffet", which has remained in the middle gender, but in the masculine it has endings according to the model "castle".
