Scattered houses flood the Czech Republic, families have no money to finish them
Prices for building materials have risen by more than 30 per cent in recent weeks and months.
Many people have found themselves in a difficult situation because of this.
She does not have the means to complete the family homes she has already built, and the banks are refusing to increase her mortgage loans.
In addition to the price of materials, the price of construction work is also increasing.
People therefore do not have enough money to finish the family homes that have already been laid out.
In many cases, banks refuse to increase mortgage loans, which creates extremely unpleasant situations.
In the best case, people move into makeshift and unlicenced houses.
In the worst case scenario, the scattered houses are uninhabitable, and families are forced to sell them because they cannot afford to pay off the mortgage and rent at the same time," says BHS economist Štěpán Křeček.
We build two to three family homes a year, and fifty percent of the time it happens to us.
For us, as a construction company, it is difficult, because we have to comply with some of the contractual obligations, even though the materials have become more expensive.
So we're doing it for free," said Zdeněk Slivoň, the owner of a construction company.
There are a lot of people who are going to have financial problems.
If they were counting on it costing five million to build the house, now it will cost seven.
I think some will wait," added Slivoň.
Copper, iron and also plumbing and heating equipment were the most expensive items.
Construction firms are also struggling with a shortage of labour.
In the Czech Republic, there is a lack of graduates in construction-related fields, and the influx of foreign workers is being slowed by the pandemic.
The situation is currently more favourable with regard to the issuing of building permits.
"The building authorities issued 7,675 building permits in October, which is almost 10 percent more than a year ago," said Křeček.
We are doing well, and we will do even better.
