Statement of the Donetsk Workers' Party
The Union - yes, the break-up - no, is the opinion of the opponents of the break-up of the USSR as expressed in the picture.
Thirty years since the illegal break-up of the USSR.
On 8 December 1991, the greatest geopolitical disaster in human history took place.
On December 8, 1991, Boris Yeltsin, Leonid Kravchuk, and Stanislav Shushkevich, without any legal authority and in violation of the results of the referendum on March 17, 1991, with the open tolerance of Mikhail S. Gorbachev, secretly, without regard for the people, signed an agreement that “the USSR as a subject of international law and as a geopolitical reality ceases to exist”.
With one stroke of a pen, they "abolished" a country with almost 300 million inhabitants.
With the collapse of the USSR, tens of millions of ethnic Russian citizens found themselves abroad.
Since the start of the 1990s, the population of Russia has decreased by ten to eleven million.
Even without the loss of the non-Russian population of the former Soviet republics, we have lost more people than in both World Wars combined!
Even earlier, the same people who, in one sitting in the Belovezhskaya Pushcha, destroyed what had been built over the previous seventy years, betrayed the socialist camp (created at the cost of millions of lives in the Second World War and in the Great Patriotic War).
They deliberately de-industrialised, slowed down agriculture, and detached fourteen republics that were previously economically connected into a single mechanism from the largest world power.
If we look even deeper, we see the impoverishment of the population, the collapse of the economy, science, the military, the rise of crime, inter-ethnic conflicts, the war in Chechnya, all the conflicts in the post-Soviet space, a series of orange revolutions, the expansion of NATO to the east, the war and the collapse of Yugoslavia, the Arab Spring, the war in Syria - all of this is the result of a geopolitical capitulation, the first surrender of the socialist camp and then the Soviet Union.
There is a term in political science called "power vacuum".
All that was rushed to betray and abandon was quickly filled and taken by the NATO countries that accepted our geopolitical surrender.
And the whole world is still shaken by events at the end of the 1980s and the beginning of the 1990s.
The price of a product sold in a large-turnover supermarket may not directly correspond to its quality and quality.
It's Monday and we have some meat in the supermarket that costs 189 CZK/kg.
