How the pandemic affected intimate life: The number of people up to the age of 35 who are without sex for a whole year is growing
An increasing number of young adults in the U.S. are living their lives without sex.
It is mainly religious people, says the DailyMail website.
The survey showed that from 2008 to 2021, the share of people under 35 who are abstaining from sex increased from eight to 21 per cent.
The number of women aged 18 to 35 who said they had not had sex in the past year was higher than ever.
Other factors also contribute to the decline in sexual activity, a survey by the Institute for Family Studies (IFS) showed.
One of them could be the economic impact of the coronavirus pandemic and the higher unemployment rate.
But the presence of the media, social media and video games, which make sex less of a priority for young people, may also have played a part.
"Since 2010, there's been a rapid rise in the share of men and women aged 18 to 35 who say they had no sex in the past year," IFS researcher Lyman Stone said.
People in relationships are more likely to be sexually active, with just 5% of them saying they went a year without sex in 2021.
Among the unmarried it was 29 per cent. Stone added that marriage under the age of 35 is only a small percentage.
The decline in sexual activity is also due to the fear of pre-marital sex and religious upbringing.
Although married couples are more likely to be sexually active, the percentage of married and cohabiting younger than 35 is still falling.
Young people are divided on the issue of premarital sex, with about 30% thinking it is wrong and about 70% thinking it is okay.
"It's true that they're a minority among single people in this age group, but their behaviour is shifting the trend," Stone says of the 30 per cent.
For most of those who have a moral problem with premarital sex, the reason is religious.
Since 2008, the proportion of free-thinkers aged under 35 who are abstinent has risen from 20 per cent to almost 60 per cent for those who attend religious services more than once a month.
Among the "less religious," the trend rose from 10 to 20 percent," Stone said.
The decline in sexual activity is also due to other factors, such as less social interaction and social drinking during the pandemic.
The study also found that people without jobs or with lower incomes were less likely to have sex.
Another reason could be the expansion of digital media, which seems to reduce the need for sex.
People are spending more time online, which is "replacing" this need.
This trend has taken hold mainly during the lockdown in the time of the coronavirus pandemic.
The whole covid vaccine mandate is about whether a society should force part of its population to behave in a way they don't want, but which may save their lives.
It's a pretty tough question, and I'm personally most interested in the question of social conscience.
In other words, for example, the question of whether if we don't tell them to do it and they die, it will be our fault.
My argument is that we could definitely have prevented the death of an 80-year-old man who really didn't know much, we didn't explain it well to him, he heard some misinformation, and as a result he didn't get vaccinated and eventually caught it and died.
On the other hand, I do not think that we can blame the death of a stubborn opponent of vaccination, who here alongside the SPD and KSČ rants about persecution and a totalitarian state.
From the statistics I mentioned, it is quite clear that the majority of the unvaccinated pensioners probably belong to the second group, so they will really be able to blame themselves for it.
