Hugo the dog is doing his best.
Juraj Šajmovič, however, did not keep an eye on his film.
Czech family comedy creators have looked at American stories about beloved dogs.
However, they forgot one important thing: the laws of the film industry.
After the kitsch film F. Brabec's Gump - the dog who taught people to live, the film Tady hlídáme my is now competing for the audience's emotions in cinemas.
The co-scriptwriter and director in one person, Juraj Šajmovič Jr., freely builds on his previous film Tady hlídám já from 2012.
The talking hedgehog, Hugo, is back on the scene, along with some familiar faces.
Julie and Ivan, the owners of a Šumava pension that is dying, and so they start to call in dog walkers, Julie's father with his partner and above all her daughter Veronika.
She is no longer a little girl, but a young woman experiencing her first love.
The director, together with his partner Beatriz Šajmovičová (who is also the film’s producer), struggled with the storytelling in the previous dog film, but at least the children and the dog were amused.
This time, the writing duo has written an even weaker script, which provokes a mixture of awe and feelings of embarrassment.
Let's recap.
Julie, despite being a scientist, succumbs to the darkness of her desire for a child and when the right "constellation" occurs, she copulates with her forest engineer Ivan, wherever the coordinates determine - on the bonnet of a car or a church tower (of course, during a guided tour with a local guide), the retired colonel Mojmír, despite years of training, shoots his own daughter (Julie) in the forest, who falls into a coma, after which she is taken to the hospital by her family so that a miraculous process of healing can take place in the heart of the Šumava wilderness.
Nothing wrong with the restorative power of nature and the strength of animal companions.
Their owners know why they have them.
The viewer, however, can't help but wonder how much of this content pelmel full of unbelievable situations and figures was needed to convey this message.
A couple of thieves from the staff, a dog show, a Šumava charlatan, police officers arriving on the tip to look for "drugs" and discuss the fertilizing power of bone meal - and the baked family at the pension, of course, gets drunk.
When the heroine, after a long coma, wakes up and immediately sits down at the family table, made-up and with a cigarette, and demands her father's whiskey and some meat as a recovered vegetarian, you can't help but laugh.
On top of that, the creators explain to the viewer that "this sometimes happens after a coma."
Šajmovič's team lacks basic dramaturgical knowledge of working with the text, the ability to build the main situation, a sense of the characters' characters and the point, and directorial guidance.
The acting is uneven, the editing aimless, and the overall impression muddled.
No matter how hard Lukáš Vaculík, Jitka Ježková or Nela Boudová try to keep their parties going, they don't have much to play with.
The only positive aspect of the film is the poetic shots of the Šumava nature by cameraman Vladimír Holomka and the pair of dachshunds.
It's not enough to sketch out a few characters, a flimsy plot and some dog jokes, let alone the more common vulgar terms the characters use.
Even long-term membership of the Dachshund Club - as in the case of the producer - is not an argument.
Good intentions to promote nature and the friendship between man and dog must be accompanied by the knowledge of the craft, if one wants to tell a believable story.
This was not successful in this case.
There's a bit too much eroticism and a minimum of feeling for the genre in a good family picture.
Even as an advert for canine therapy, this amateurishly-conceived piece wouldn't pass muster.
