The Middle East is experiencing unusually dry months.
Winter is the only time of the year when it rains.
"The nearly complete absence of precipitation during November, as recorded at some stations, is unusual," the Israel Meteorological Service confirms.
For example, the village of Kfar Giladi in northern Israel reported just six percent of its long-term average rainfall for November.
This week's two-day storm was therefore more of an exception.
It's good for us.
It hasn't rained for a long time.
It's also the right Christmas backdrop, said Wasim Ashkar, a resident of Nazareth.
Precipitation in Israel comes almost exclusively in the winter months, is sporadic and irregular.
Forests are dependent on winter rains.
Without them, they dry up and are prone to fires.
It's not just about the forests, but also about drinking water supplies and irrigation for farmers.
Israel's largest freshwater source, the Sea of Galilee, filled to its brim this spring for the first time in three years, thanks to three rainy winters in a row.
Since then, the level has fallen.
The water managers have been warning about the drought for a long time.
"It is expected that as a result of global warming and climate change, there may be a decrease in rainfall in this area," Uri Schor, a spokesperson for the Israel Water Authority, said in 2018.
Israel can help itself with technologies such as desalination and recycling of waste water.
Economically weaker countries such as Lebanon, Syria and Jordan are worse off.
In the streets of Jordan's capital, Amman, tanker trucks are becoming more common.
Water pipes and private wells are drying up.
"This year I've seen a 70 to 80 percent increase in orders compared to the past two years," tanker truck driver Imad Suleiman said in September.
Clashes broke out between farmers and security forces in the Iranian city of Isfahan.
The drought was the reason for the protests.
The local riverbed was completely dry.
The region has had one of the driest Novembers in recent years.
