Another government ends and the law on the involvement of municipalities in the selection of a storage facility is nowhere to be found
Minister Karel Havlíček's proposal needs major revision
The government of Prime Minister Andrej Babiš is coming to an end and the law that was supposed to ensure respect for the interests of local communities and their citizens in the selection and permitting of a deep geological repository for high-level radioactive waste still does not exist.
The government's legislative council suspended the discussion of the proposal, which the Ministry of Industry and Trade submitted to the government after years of delays.
However, its content is in serious conflict not only with the affected municipalities united in the Platform Against the Deep Repository, but also with the Union of Towns and Municipalities of the Czech Republic.
Local authorities are legally entitled to expect a significant strengthening of their decision-making powers in relation to storage sites, which has been promised to mayors since 2011, when work on this legislation began, and which is required by the Czech Atomic Act and the European Directive.
We expect the new government to revise the proposal in line with its coalition agreement in cooperation with the municipalities.
The draft law proposed by Minister Karel Havlíček, which the Platform has access to, is criticised by municipalities primarily for the following: The proposed level of involvement of municipalities and the public in the decision-making process regarding the selection of a site for a storage facility is insufficient and cannot ensure the respect of the interests of municipalities and their citizens.
It is only truly effective if communities or the public can influence whether the process will continue at a particular site.
This can be achieved by placing a duty on the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority to seek the consent of the affected local authorities before beginning a specific process.
The proposed real estate plan almost completely ignores the involvement of the public and turns the citizens of the municipalities into mere extras in the permit proceedings.
The draft lacks a system-wide compensation setting for municipalities for the entire process of locating and selecting a storage site, its licensing and operation.
According to today's legal norms, the representatives of the municipalities do not have many options for defending the interests of their citizens in the search for a storage site.
Only in some permitting proceedings can they submit their comments or appeal, but the decision is made by the authority or the minister in whose interest it is to issue the permit.
A possible lawsuit does not have a suspensive effect on the performance of survey or construction works.
Co-determination of local authorities, which the Platform is calling for, is a common principle in many democratically advanced countries, and certainly in those that have already advanced in the permitting of repositories, such as Sweden and Finland.
The preparation of the law is another failure of the state administration, which hires external law firms to prepare legislation.
In this case, it is a contract with the law firm HAVEL & PARTNERS s.r.o., which SÚRAO signed and follows on from contracts with the lawyer Jan Zemánek.
According to the register of contracts, the total sum for this work is almost 4 million Czech crowns.
Antonín Seknička, Deputy Mayor of Cejle from the Hrádek area and spokesperson for the Platform Against a Deep Geological Repository, said: After the ministers of industry, who only pushed back the position of local self-government bodies in relation to state authorities in the search for a deep geological repository for highly radioactive waste, we are waiting for a significant turnaround from the new government.
We are also offering a helping hand.
We would also like to thank the Association of Towns and Municipalities, which shares the view of the directly affected municipalities in selected localities that the rights of municipalities are insufficient for such a major construction.
The platform against a deep storage facility brings together 51 members (35 municipalities and cities and 16 associations) to push for a change in the state's approach to dealing with spent nuclear fuel and other radioactive waste, which will not be limited to a deep storage facility.
The platform also advocates that the decision on the selection of a site for the possible storage should be subject to the prior approval of the affected municipalities.
John Goodman (69) was forced to lose weight out of fear: He lost 90 kg.
Although he didn't feel the need to change his lifestyle for a long time, in the end it was the doctors who scared him.
They told him that if he didn't lose weight, he would die.
And it worked.
Mr Goodman has lost a total of 90kg, which is half his original weight of 180kg, The Sun reports.
He showed off his new look at the premiere of the animated series The Freak Brothers in Los Angeles.
The fat guy from the Roseanne sitcom is a completely different person!
John liked to joke that his friends and family urged him to lose weight because his large body caused furniture to break.
"I was eating everything," the actor said in a 2018 interview with AARP.
This time, I wanted to do it slowly.
Move, exercise.
I'm getting to an age where I can't afford to sit on my backside any more, he told ABC, whose transformation is remarkable.
Also, it depends on what kind of boss and in what context you want to use the word "boss".
If it's some text on a platform that expects readers from a gaming environment, I wouldn't translate it at all.
If it was a formal text, perhaps a university essay, I would probably be looking for ways to describe or explain the boss.
To top it off, there are different kinds of bosses.
For example, a game like Dark Souls etc. has multiple bosses, yes, and so a "boss" is something like a lord/ruler of a given level, and then there's the final boss...
In many games, there are hidden bosses (super bosses, hidden bosses), which are not required to be beaten in order to complete the game or level, but are often more powerful than standard bosses.
Then there are games like Half-Life, where there are bosses, but the player doesn't fight them directly (Tentacle, Gargantua), and can they be called bosses at all?
And then there are the mini-bosses.
In fact, it is difficult to translate the word boss in one word. Czech and other languages do not deal with this issue (the Catalan language is interesting in this regard, as it translates boss as the final opponent).
It's a computer-controlled opponent that is important to the story or the game in general, stronger than all the previous ones and guarding the completion of some level or task.
